reviewText: Frontier Marshal, what a surprice. It's about Wyatt Earp and Doc Holiday ( here called Haliday for some reason )and then there are so many similarities to John Fords "My Darling Clementine" which were made some years later. It's even the same actor ( Charles Stevens ) who plays the drunken indian in the beginning of the movies. I guessed it. Both films are built on the same novel. This film does not reach the Charles Dickens-like virtuosity of John Ford's masterpiece but it is of no consequence. Director Dwan's version is a b-western masterpiece. Randolph Scott is a convincing Wyatt Earp ( of course )and Cesar Romero is an all times Doc and the whole film is indeed worth seeing and knowing. The gunfight at the OK Corral is a bit too hasty done with, though. Last but not least the dvd is knife sharp, it is like being in the movie theater. Warm recommandations!
Title: N/A

reviewText: I'm an avid collector of movies. It was my escape as a child. I had not seen this version until this evening. And I was very impressed with this version. I do the similarities between this version and "My Darling Clementine." Anyone expecting "historical accuracy" s being nave, even delusional. This is Hollywood film making & they take license with any story-line. Certainly there are flaws with a 1939 film that's a "B" western. But this is a well made Western with Randolph Scott as Wyatt Earp and a credible Cesar Romero as Doc Holliday. You also get to see Lon Chaney, Jr. and John Carradine as the villains.
summary: Great movie to compare with Ford's masterpiece
